Global : 
  git config --list
  
  git config --global --unset user.name
  git config --global --unset user.email
  
  git config --global user.name "Anisha-Paturi"
  git config --global user.email "paturi.anisha@gmail.com"
  
  git config --list


SSH : 
  Delete Old Key : 
    cd %USERPROFILE%\.ssh
    dir
    del *
    dir
    cd ..

  Generate a new SSH key : 
    ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "paturi.anisha@gmail.com"
    Then the terminal will ask:
      Enter file to save key → press ENTER
      Enter passphrase → press ENTER
      Confirm passphrase → press ENTER
      This creates two files inside .ssh:
          id_ed25519 → private key
          id_ed25519.pub → public key (this goes to GitHub)
  In Git Bash:
    eval $(ssh-agent -s) -> This starts the agent.
    Add your key: ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
    If successful it says: Identity added: /home/.../id_ed25519

Copy the PUBLIC key to GitHub :
  cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
  Copy the ENTIRE output.
  Then : 
  Go to GitHub
  Settings → SSH and GPG Keys
  New SSH Key
  Paste → Save
  Done.

Test your SSH connection : 
Run: ssh -T git@github.com
If everything is correct, you'll get: Hi <your-username>! You've successfully authenticated.

Set up your Git repo
  Now connect your project folder.
  Open Git Bash in your project:
  git init
  git add .
  git commit -m "Initial commit"

Go to GitHub → Create new repo → Select SSH URL, looks like:
git@github.com:username/repo-name.git
Add remote : git remote add origin git@github.com:username/repo-name.git
Push : git push -u origin main


